   African Growth and Opportunity Act
   [agoa1.jpg] [agoa2.jpg] [agoa3.jpg] [agoa4.jpg]
   [clearpixel.gif] [clearpixel.gif]

   President Clinton signed the African Growth and Opportunity Act (AGOA)
   into law on May 18, 2000 as Title 1 of The Trade and Development Act of
   2000. The Act offers tangible incentives for African countries to
   continue their efforts to open their economies and build free markets.

   AGOA UPDATE:

   PRESIDENT BUSH APPROVES AGOA TRADE BENEFITS FOR 35 COUNTRIES AFTER
   ANNUAL REVIEW

   REPORT OF FIRST U.S. - SUB-SAHARAN AFRICAN TRADE AND ECONOMIC
   COOPERATION FORUM, OCTOBER 29-30, 2001

   The first AGOA Forum was held in Washington, DC October 29-30, 2001.
   President Bush and four Cabinet members, ministers from the 35
   AGOA-eligible countries, representatives of African regional
   organizations, the U.S. and African private sectors, and
   non-governmental organizations participated in this historic event.

   AGOA FORUM NEWSLETTER

   U.S. - SUB-SAHARAN AFRICA TRADE STATISTICS  (JANUARY - SEPTEMBER  2001)



